The first virtual operator is going to arrive this year in the Czech Republic.
Probably.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It probably won't be long before we get there.
That Czech operators are part of the most expensive in Europe, we have already written on mobile.cz.
The rest also confirmed that the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTU) has warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is the most expensive in the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulating roaming fees, it is likely to become paradoxical - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS sending from abroad will be cheaper than sending them from home.
How can prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lacks competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical, because we have three mobile networks and its high coverage is over 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
Also the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTú), Pavel Dvořák, has already said that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a marked price drop to which the classic operators must also react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to the market in Britain, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It has been shown that there is room for such operators and that they can be successful.
Otherwise, there is no need to look for examples too far.
In February of this year we inform you about the launch of the Virtual Mobilking operator in Poland.
Only after half a year did this operator obtain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighbouring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking there is the Penta group that, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is that they can concentrate on many more specific target groups.
In addition, in order for them to function effectively, they are enough with many fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry with them relatively large costs in construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world this type of virtual operators are usually profiled with low expenses - they offer cheap SMS calls and messages that however, often goes against the offer of more adjusted services.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in Britain offers at least half of the cost-effective SMS with respect to competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it may also be a good blow to bet by a trivial target group.
This operator specifically addresses the man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - it is the operator who likes and who can be trusted," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept as that of Poland could be involved in our country.
From this, Vodafone spokesperson Miroslav Čepický doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition from the point of view of the supply of services it is relatively saturated"
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if in the Czech Republic there will be any virtual operator that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic does not seem to be too hopeful.
Rather, it's about the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region," he said in a phone conversation for mobile.cz, Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
Indirectly he assured that current mobile telephone operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything they can to ensure that no potential competition arises.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step forward to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, in order to offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile phone services.
And how much sooner, better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly met with all Czech mobile telephony operators.
With some of them we have made progress in the meetings," said the group spokesperson Pavel Kaidl.
So, maybe they'll light up better times.
It seems that, for unofficial information, the first official operator would possibly have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now its appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment we believe that the situation is suitable for the appearance of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this field," he said for mobile.cz, Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesman for Telefónica O2.
The specific features of the Czech market concern other operators.
T-mobile spokesperson Martina Kemrová, in exceptional accordance with the opinion of O2, adds: "So far we have not registered any viable commercial projects that can, bilaterally beneficial, continue to develop."
And he adds: "On the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find some virtual operators until the end of the year.
At this point we should have on the table some concrete contract that could be studied on such a short horizon."
Vodafone directs its attention rather than to the fulfilment of the proper requirements of a 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of cost and infrastructure sharing.
We consider this to be the biggest customer contribution.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field is the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet on mobile."
Responsible offices - with operators and meat
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a fall in prices and thus a decrease in profits.
Then why facilitate entry into competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull from the same rope, proof of it is the grip when U:fon came up.
Perhaps the greatest pressure to ČTÚ was at the time of the entry of U:phon by the T-Mobile society.
Public information accessible on ČTú websites attests to this.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds to this: "In addition, not long ago the competitive environment in the mobile telephony market was open to a fourth operator.
With regard to the nature of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would entail for him and, above all, for his services great requirements."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
It is not just the ČTU's position, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in trade tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Auctions (UOHS).
However, she expressed her typical attitude to this problem.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after a convention on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator was closed.
To date, no agreement has been closed since the offer of interested potentials was not interesting enough for classic operators," added Kristián Chalupa, of the UOHS Department of External Relations.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of operators.
For the offices that should represent the interests of consumers it is something more than a consideration, besides that they must note that no one takes advantage of their position on the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Foreign where virtual operators work normally we can see that their market entry contributed to the price drop in mobile telephony services"
Of course, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market media and the fall in prices does not fall within the UOHS interest.
Truly the dramatic shock in all this case lies in the dissonant reactions resulting from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence, it is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline in the gas stations, as it is clear that it is the work of chance and a hard struggle for competition.
"The Office has not found any sign of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position therefore have a corresponding rise of responsibility in their market actions.
The tools needed to open the mobile telephony market to virtual operators, rather, are missing as well as telecommunications regulators," added Chalupa.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many conflicting points.
Obviously there is an analysis of relevant markets drawn up by ČTÚ that telecommunications are from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of Czech operators have a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another view - for a virtual operator to arise it is always necessary to agree with the network administrator.
And the mobile telephony operator - with all its logic - has the monopoly of its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must be necessarily dominant.
And if this argument was not accepted, at least for UOHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators rise remarkably in a similar manner.
The current complaints from stakeholders (inspired by the aforementioned GTS Novera company) show that in all negotiations with operators they collide with many similar impediments.
Loading responsibility at ČTÚ is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which UOHS washes its hands in this whole matter.
We have already met with him in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law for the extension of ČTU's competence in the field of trade tenders was introduced recently, even though a number of experts promised that the situation would improve.
This should be well known to UOHS representatives, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
It's all right, when no one's looking
At the same time, unobviously something like a pseudovirtual operator continues to work, which already exists a few in Czech mobile networks.
They are companies that put their own prices to mobile telephony services which, however, only a part are public.
These are usually multi-level marketing companies.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a few chosen get the price list of these companies.
Magic is in which the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the company by charging a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile telephony operators prohibit such resale.
"If cases such as those cited could be discovered, they could talk about infringement in terms of contract conditions that could be translated into the end of collaboration with the given company," answered the question about this problem Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity by mobile telephony operators would not reach responsible people.
Precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned can come to be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies, they get no negligible profits and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of possible problems: "the law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a contemptible so many percent of customers.
They must also accept that your phone's SIM card is not in your name so they cannot absolutely dispose of it as a normal customer of operators."
This is precisely what ČTU should think of as minimally strange.
There is also a new question for UOHS.
If mobile telephony operators surround the eyes in this type of procedure, why block the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that UOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and if it is not going to want it it must not be satisfied with the explanations of operators that they have no idea of this story and that its commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As already made clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market led to a significant decline in service prices.
At the same time, practically in all countries where the virtual operator emerged, classical operators tried to protect themselves more or less from this disruption.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market, possibly too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, the regulatory bodies have now intervened and in none of the cases defended operators but their customers.
Out with formal measures or informal pressure, the first virtual operator emerged and others began to emerge with it.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body all this case happens as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot help but be impressed that the confusion of powers in these cases suits them.
But let's not despair.
If this information between the background is correct and the virtual operator actually reaches these lands, then the Czech mobile telephony market will probably start moving again.
If one of the operators lets a virtual mobile telephony operator enter, it will be difficult for UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four presentations of the new Czech official anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the Czech official celebrations presented the new official anthem recording Where, my home.
The new anthem was recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are Solos, one male voice and one female voice, one with Chorus and another instrumental.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka are assigned to the song.
The authors of the anthem arrangements are Otakar Jeremiaš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to the four versions.
Bělohlávek considers this Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
The Czech Radio has already said that it intentionally elected for the solo singers with representatively young voices that are more expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried with the two and then, too, with the Choir to be fixed in the diction so that the text would be understood well, so that it would have consonance," he said.
The Czech official anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where, my Home played for the first time in 1834 on the tables of the State Theatre in the Czech work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged with the music of František Škroup.
He won popularity and people made it his own.
The first stanza of the song following the emergence of Czechoslovakia in 1918 became, naturally, part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
