In cases where the manifestation is very intense it would be appropriate to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any question that is generating much anxiety and gives him out in this way.
We have said it is a benign alteration, therefore it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (e.g. if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress table).
What you can do is take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child much before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid TV shows or TV series that are either scared or a little violent.
With very nervous children and who find it hard to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain a certain inner calm.
This will help the child to have a quieter dream.
Once the sleepwalks appear try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what has happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his dream.
Even if he's talking, he's sleeping and so he's resting.
Remember that if you are very distressed during various episodes you should check out or find out what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he is saying (which is not the usual), do not fall into the temptation to interrogate him for information.
You won't get anything, because when you're asleep you're not aware of how to organize your thinking.
Also you will hear what it says, but you do not know what it is dreaming to say that, so be very careful how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to know his secrets.
Not even a joke.
That generates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
