Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most important economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US$700 billion plan that seeks to curb the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months has yet to be confirmed by both Houses of Congress.
It foresees in particular: better control by the electors of their implementation, new mechanisms that seek to ensure the reimbursement of public money invested, new provisions to contain the number of embarked houses the lack of payment, as well as a right of control over wages paid to the leaders of the assisted companies.
The US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, the President of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, at the end of a negotiating marathon lasted two days.
" We are making great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said the representative of the Bush administration, Henry Paulson.
" Everything has been done to cover the economy and ordinary Americans in the face of the current Wall Street crisis," the Democrat explained.
"It is the fundamental point: if we do not do this, trauma, chaos and disturbances on the daily life of Americans will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had ended very quickly in the last few hours because they feared the effect of a further failure on the mood of investors.
The last hour that had been set was the opening up of markets this morning.
The two candidates in the American presidential elections, who have been late in the negotiations, were rather favourable to the agreement, while not forgetting to express their discontent of being forced to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama was given certain provisions to reach the agreement, particularly the one that would allow the owners to retain their domicile and the salary of the leaders of state-survivors.
" When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is no need to congratulate themselves.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on American television.
His Republican opponent, John McCain, interrogated in another chain to know if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied that "I would like to see the details, but I hope to vote on it."
"The important points I read [show] that it is something we will have to digest and with which we will be able to advance.
He said that the option of not doing anything is not acceptable ".
The plan of 700 billion aims to buy with taxpayers' money the dubious debts, the risk and unsold assets of the American financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis caused by the outbreak of a real estate bubble that first led to the sinking of mortgage risk credits before extending to other more common forms of credit securities (PCAA) and leading to a freezing of liquidity and a breakdown of banks and financial institutions.
It is a group of elected Republicans who had changed the first draft agreement last week.
We believe that we have emerged from the stagnation since the Democrats accepted that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
With the aim of clearing roughness for everyone in Congress, we also added a provision that provided that if the government had to take losses for five years with this program, it could impose new fees that would help it recover money.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first part of 250 billion, to which an additional 100 billion may be added if the President considers it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion would have to be confirmed by another vote by Congress.
Instead of helping you, Washington will get shares in the rescue companies that will be worth dividends in the event of profits and that it will be able to sell again when the storm is over.
The federal government will have the possibility of delaying the embargo procedures relating to housing obtained with real estate loans under this plan, as well as setting limits on remuneration and cash compensation paid to the leaders of the companies affected by the crisis.
The architects of the plan would like to see him put to the vote by the House of Representatives today and by the Senate next Wednesday.
Despite all its efforts, it is not yet certain that its plan will be approved.
Some people continued to protest this project yesterday, both on the part of Republicans and Democrats.
Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Commission, told his constituents that "with all evidence, Washington does not want to understand ".
" We have a very serious financial problem.
There are some solutions.
But not the one that consists of taking advantage of taxpayers ".
Democratic representative Brad Sherman, who is an animator of a small group in Congress, presents the problems differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred economic professors, including three Nobel Prizes, wrote to tell us: we ask Congress not to rush and carefully examine the path to be taken," he said yesterday.
At this very moment, in Europe, we again had the proof of the global nature of the crisis.
After an urgent meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group by 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion dollars).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it had renounced buying its competitor in bankruptcy since it lost EUR 2 billion ($2.9 billion) during the crisis of risk real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85 000 people and is part of the 20 largest European banks and the ten largest insurers.
"This is not lost money, declared yesterday the Dutch Minister of Finance, Wouter Bos.
Instead, we regain a right to vote in the bank and influence.
