The smart car imitates the flight of the bulldozer
What would be the best way to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of existing obstacles sensors in nature?
For example that of the suburbs.
In a surprising project presented at the CEATEC in Japan, the Beejorres gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
The Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the robotic steering system of BR23C-like cars that mimic nature, to which they gave the characteristics of the bullfighters, with the ultimate aim of creating a system that can dodge all the collisions.
During the flight each bulldozer creates its own ovulated private space that actually looks a lot like our safety protective capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, technological director of PR and development and research.
An important role is played by the eyes composed of the beekeepers that are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the composite eyes, the engineers used the laser beam length measurement system.
This identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the vehicle microprocessor that immediately turns into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle mimicking the movements of the beehives, modifies the direction by rotating the wheels as necessary.
Unlike any existing system, this maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If not, the robot of the vehicle could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and of the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the protective safety capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what makes a beehive to dodge other beehives.
This process must be carried out in a opening and closing of the eyes.
However, unlike the beeholes, the movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonals, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of turning the wheels
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for the bees to dodge other bees, here only used as a possibility for the robot of the car the rotational movement and acceleration in addition the braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and its energy density is higher, which means they have a longer life span than that of lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the data processing capacity, not much less the storage capacity.
This device in every second should only process some input signals and react as appropriate.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data from the previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
There's no need for gigabytes or megabytes.
This is the first step to develop the technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which according to Nissan calculations, within ten years can be incorporated into the models manufactured in series.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, avoiding existing obstacles on his way.
