Industrial prices continue to increase
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to last month prices and 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 prices - reported by the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH).
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 per cent compared to the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent over the previous month and by 3.2 per cent over the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased only to a minimum, with 0.1 per cent.
Internal sales prices in the processing industry increased by at least 0.1 per cent compared to July.
The largest increase in prices occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 per cent), primarily due to an increase of 4.6 per cent per month in bags and belts and an increase of 2.5 per cent in footwear.
The highest price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical material production branch (1.6 percent).
There was a price decrease in the petrochemical sector, (1.4 per cent), in the production of electric machines and instruments (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimum extent - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 per cent).
The prices of papermaking, publishing and printing did not change.
In the rest of the processing industry there was an increase in prices between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent a significant weight within internal trade, an increase of 0.3 per cent was recorded in August, first of all as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from the first of July.
In a comparison of a period of 12 months - in the domestic sales of the processing industry - the largest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 percent).
In the metal processing sector, an increase of 13.2 per cent was observed, while in the food, beverages and tobacco industry, of determining weight, there was an increase of 11 per cent.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 per cent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Over the past year in the processing industry globally increased prices by 10.2 percent.
The prices of electricity, the supply of gas, heat and water exceeded 18.7 percent of the prices of the previous year.
In August, the largest monthly increase in prices (0.7 per cent) was recorded among the different sectors of domestic trade in investment goods.
In the consumer sector, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, and in the energy sector and intermediate sector prices there were no changes compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, with respect to the same month of the previous year, the largest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8 percent).
A 6.8 per cent decrease in consumer goods was recorded in the consumer sector and 1.4 per cent in investment goods.
The export prices of the industry calculated at HUF increased by 1.1 percent over the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 percent.
The contribution of our national currency in one month was reduced by 1.7 per cent with respect to the euro and 7.1 per cent with respect to the dollar, compared to August 2007 it strengthened by 7.5 per cent with respect to the euro and 15.9 per cent with respect to the dollar.
