Jaróka: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today, the European Summit for Equal Opportunities has been launched in Paris. Its host is France, who is also President of the European Union this year.
Lívia Járóka, Member of the European People's Party for Fides, in her message addressed to the plenary, as one of the main speakers of this professional meeting, drew attention to segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations that plague Roma children and is also the biggest obstacle to the prevalence of their interests.
This high-level conference was opened - on behalf of the French Presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs and by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Representatives of governments, European social partners and representatives of the most important European organisations for the protection of social rights attended the meeting.
Járóka - according to the press office of the Fidesz Group in the European Parliament - warned that in addition to discrimination in employment, Roma remain outside the labour market first because of their low level of schooling.
"Most Roma young people have not finished middle school and due to poor quality of basic education, only a small part of them can obtain university degrees."
Járóka also stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, also plays a decisive role in the prevalence of other human rights.
Investment in the education of Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the Euro MP, these issues need to be widely made aware of both Roma and non-Gypsies.
For the sooner a Gypsy student starts school, the more likely he will have to become an active member of the labour market; through income taxes and consumption they will also contribute to the national budget.
"Gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, must be guaranteed the right to a quality education and to ensure the abolition of segregated and low-level education," said Lívia Jaróka.
According to the Euro MP, the objective and active unity of the European Union is necessary in order to speed up school disaggregation processes immediately. That is why it is essential to comply with the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, we must offer Roma children the possibility which guarantees democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as full-right citizens," Jaróka said.
The aim of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities organized annually since last year's Berlin meeting in the sign of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities" is to ensure a unique forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at European and national level in the Member States.
