Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso, the cities cancel the historic halls
The historical cinemas close by favoring the Multiplex.
"A city without cinemas in a blind city, is like a face without eyes."
The image offered by director Giuseppe Tornatore photographers effectively what is happening in the large Italian urban centers and also in the provincial cities.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, which with the birth of the great meticones on the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono-rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear are almost always historical places, full of memory, "is as if a friend died, a acquaintance with whom a piece of place was shared and so much emotion," observes the director of the new cinema Paradiso, the film that 20 years ago won the cousin Oscar and the grand prize of the jury to Cannes, who recounted the poetry of a provincial cinema hall and nostalgia for the way to live the cinema that might be lost forever.
The figures given by the Anec, the main association of the traders, speak clearly: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have been closed, and most of the rooms in the main cities are to be paid: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most suffered by the closures are the first, Emilia-Romaña with 82 cinemas less, following by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the responsible for its disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, these three Italian regions are their own that have made the largest number of new methonic cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romaña.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally", notes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec," it would be useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to guarantee the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its frequenters are willing to transfer to the metrons.
Not to mention the lack of funds for traders: the state's previous debt is approximately EUR 10 million.
It is shameful from an ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
In order to support the sector it would serve between 16 and 18 million euros a year’.
Interesting the case of Bologna, the first Italian city concerned with the closures, decided to repair itself with the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of this type in Italy to promote and protect the cinema mono room is in the historical center and in the periphery.
Among the proposed rules are means of tax facilitation for managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators may enter the restricted traffic area and will have special parking fees.
"It is an initiative that I like" observes Giuseppe Tornatore" and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by setting up other measures.
It is true that in order to contrast the extra power of the metrones, traditional rooms have to improve the quality of sound and image because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is an issue that has always been important to me: the closure of Bagheria cinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to perform the "New Paradise Cinema", which I had thought of for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass before the Rialto or the Quirinale of Via Nazionale already closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, not to see the posters blackened by the dust, I turn to the other side."
